- Global bond markets: $40 trillion total
  - Investment-grade BarCap Global Aggregate: $35.2 trillion (govt $17.4T + govt-related $5.3T + corp $5.8T + securitized $6.7T)
  - HY: $1.1 trillion; EM debt: $2.5 trillion; Inflation-linked: $1.5 trillion
- Global financial assets (McKinsey 2009): $178 trillion at end-2008 (fell from $194T in 2007)
  - Equities $34T, private debt $51T, govt debt $32T, bank deposits $61T
  - Global residential real estate: $87 trillion
- Global AUM professionally managed: $53 trillion ($32T institutional, $21T retail)
  - HFs: ~$2 trillion; PE funds: ~$2 trillion
- HNWI wealth: $39 trillion (29% equities, 31% FI, 17% cash, 18% real estate, 6% alternatives)
- EM share of global equity market cap: 2% (1980) → 12% (2009), still below 30% EM share of global GDP
- US market cap/GDP: below 0.5 (1975-1985), above 1.0 (1996-2007)
- Derivative notional: $532 trillion; actual counterparty exposure: only $2.7 trillion (after netting)

**Data sources (Appendix B — key references for replication):**
- Equities: MSCI Barra (1970+), Kenneth French website (1926+), Robert Shiller (1871+), Dimson-Marsh-Staunton (1900+)
- Bonds: Barclays Capital (1970s+), CRSP (1952+), Ibbotson Associates (1926+)
- Carry strategy: Self-compiled G10 spot rates + deposit rates; base case: buy top-3 yield G10 currencies, sell bottom-3 weekly
- Trend strategy: 12-month moving average rule applied weekly to commodity futures, equity country futures, bond/rate futures, FX forwards
- Volatility strategy: Merrill Lynch Equity Volatility Arbitrage Index (1989+)
- Factor proxies: Growth = Consensus Economics GDP forecast changes; Inflation = Consensus Economics CPI forecast changes; Illiquidity = Bank of England Liquidity Index changes (with sign flipped); Volatility = Monthly VIX changes


